### Scenario narration content (use exactly this):

**Scenario 1 — Empty Memory**
Step 1: "This is physical memory — 8 empty frames, each one a slot 
where a page can live. Think of frames as numbered parking spaces."
Step 2: "P1 has arrived and needs 3 pages. Watch each page claim 
a frame — pages 0, 1, and 2 each get their own slot."
Step 3: "P1's pages are now resident in memory. Any access to these 
pages will be a fast hit — no loading needed."

**Scenario 2 — Demand Paging, No Faults**
Step 1: "Demand paging means pages are only loaded when actually 
accessed — not all at once when the process starts."
Step 2: "Two processes are running. Both fit comfortably in the 
available frames. Watch the grid fill gradually — each page loads 
only when the process first touches it."
Step 3: "All accesses are hits — green dots across the board. 
When there is enough memory, the system runs efficiently."

**Scenario 3 — Memory Becomes Full**
Step 1: "We are starting with a small frame pool — only 4 slots."
Step 2: "Processes are being added. Watch the frame grid fill up."
Step 3: "All frames are now occupied. The next page access cannot 
find a free slot. The system is at capacity — something must give."
Step 4: "When capacity is reached, every new page access becomes 
a fault. The system must now make difficult choices about what 
stays in memory and what gets evicted."

**Scenario 4 — Page Fault and Replacement**
(Use the step content written above in the JSON example)

**Scenario 5 — FIFO vs LRU**
Step 1: "We will run the same reference string twice — first with 
FIFO, then with LRU. Watch how the fault count differs."
Step 2 (FIFO run): "FIFO evicts whichever page has been in memory 
the longest — regardless of whether it is still being used. 
Sometimes this evicts a page that will be needed again very soon."
Step 3 (switch to LRU): "LRU evicts the page that has not been 
accessed for the longest time. It uses recent history as a 
predictor of future use."
Step 4: "Compare the fault counts. LRU usually wins — but not 
always. The best algorithm depends on the access pattern."

**Scenario 6 — Thrashing**
Step 1: "Thrashing occurs when a process needs far more pages than 
the available frames can hold."
Step 2: "Watch the frame grid — pages are being evicted almost 
immediately after loading. The replacement thread is running 
constantly."
Step 3: "Look at the fault count climbing rapidly. The hit ratio 
is collapsing. The process spends more time waiting for page loads 
than actually executing."
Step 4: "This is thrashing. Real operating systems detect this 
condition and either suspend the process or allocate it more 
frames. With a fixed frame pool, there is no escape."

